What are your thoughts on implementing a function like this:
func (o *Observable[v]) isClosed() bool {
	_, ok := <-o.ch
	return !ok
}

I think as you've written it, it would deadlock if the channel never receives after #isClosed() is called.
I 💯 agree & had the same sentiment! We considered something similar to this which accounted for that case (i.e. the channel is still open and blocking); however, at the time we somehow missed the fact that ok would be false when the channel is closed 😅. Tl;dr, I think it should look like this:
func (o *Observable[v]) isClosed() bool {
  select {
    case _, ok := <-o.ch:
      return !ok
    default:
      return false
}
(CC: @red-0ne)

I need to test it, but this seems to consume a message if the channel is not closed, maybe preventing the regular consumer from getting the message.
I may be lacking go channels knowledge here though.
Given the above, if we still want to have a stateless one, we could re-emit the value to the channel
func (o *Observable[v]) isClosed() bool {
  select {
    case v, ok := <-o.ch:
      if ok {
        o.ch <- v
        return false
      } else {
        return true
      }
    default:
      return false
}

It seems that select as it is a non blocking receive would do the trick. If the channel is closed it will always return. Which makes me think that this would suffice
func (o *Observable[v]) isClosed() bool {
    select {
    case <-o.ch:
        return true
    default:
        return false
    }
}

